<DOC><DOCNO> AP880528-0063 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0720EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-SouthAsia-Floods     05-28 0218</FIRST><SECOND>PM-South Asia-Floods,0223</SECOND><HEAD>Rains, Snow Pushing Rivers Over Banks</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The death toll from flooding innortheastern India rose to 26 today and officials in neighboringBangladesh said thousands of families were rendered homeless byrivers that overflowed their banks.   Heavy rain continued to hamper rescue workers in the northeastIndian state of Assam, where the Brahmaputra River and itstributaries have been rising for six days, the Press Trust of Indiareported.   Thousands of acres of farmland have been inundated and thousandsof families have moved to make-shift camps on higher ground, thenews agency said.   In Dhaka, the capital of Bangladesh, officials in the WaterControl Ministry said rivers were being swelled by the annual snowmelt from the Himalayan mountains and heavy, pre-monsoon rains.   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said morethan 200,000 acres of land had been flooded. They said that if thewater did not recede soon, some of the country's rice crop would bedestroyed.   More than 5,000 people were reported marooned in the tea-growingdistrict of Sylhet in northeastern Bangladesh.   Rice is the staple food for Bangladesh's 105 million people. Thecountry last year was hard-hit by floods. Nearly one-quarter of itspopulation was dislocated at the height of rain problems lastsummer.</TEXT></DOC>